Which law of thermodynamics states that the entropy of a perfect crystal at absolute zero is exactly equal to zero?

#pagebreak()
#set page(width: a_width, margin: a_margin)
#set text(size: a_size)
The Zeroth Law

#pagebreak()
#set page(width: a_width, margin: a_margin)
#set text(size: a_size)
The First Law

#pagebreak()
#set page(width: a_width, margin: a_margin)
#set text(size: a_size)
The Second Law

#pagebreak()
#set page(width: a_width, margin: a_margin)
#set text(size: a_size)
The Third Law

#pagebreak()
#set page(width: a_width, margin: a_margin)
#set text(size: a_size)
The Third Law of Thermodynamics provides an absolute reference point for the determination of entropy. It states that the entropy of a system approaches a constant value as its temperature approaches absolute zero. For a perfect crystal, this value is zero.

#pagebreak()
#set page(width: i_width, height: auto, margin: i_margin)
#set text(size: i_size)
*Prerequisites for Laws of Thermodynamics:*

- Entropy ($S$): A measure of the molecular disorder or randomness of a system.
- Absolute Zero ($0 K$): The lowest possible temperature, where thermal motion reaches a minimum.
- Perfect Crystal: A crystal with no defects or impurities.
